answers.body_markdown:
This loop runs as long as the destination pointer points to a character. The loop should have been written as

        while (*dest != &#39;\0&#39;) {
            dest++;
        }

It will produce exactly the same result but is much more readable.

After the loop the destination pointer points to the `&#39;\0&#39;` as the end-of-string character.

The loop

    while(*dst++)
       { /*empty loop body */ }

executes until `dst` points to a null character. _But it always increments `dst` so after the loop `dst` points beyond the null character and therefore a `dst--;` must be done._

`*dst++` means to evaluate if `*dst` is a null character, then increment the pointer and if it was a null character, exit the loop. Users _the busybee_&#39;s answer shows a better way of writing the loop.

@The busybee answered your question correctly.

Note that this code could have been expressed even clearlier with an extra variable using this code.

```c++
int i=0;
while(dest[i] != &#39;\0&#39;) {
    i++;
}
i--;
```
The &quot;number of character optimisations&quot; made in the original code are:
```
*i &lt;=&gt; i[0]
&#39;\0&#39; &lt;=&gt; 0
*x is applied before x++ in *x++
```

For starters this array

     char str1[20];

is not initialized and does not contain a string. So the call of the function

    strcat_p(str1, &quot;, world!&quot;);

results in undefined behavior.

The function is also declared incorrectly. It should be declared like

    char * strcat_p( char *dest, const char *src );

The implementation of the function is confusing.

It can be defined the following way

    char * strcat_p( char *dest, const char *src )
    {
        char *p = dest;

        while( *p != &#39;\0&#39; ) ++p;

        do
        {
            *p++ = *src;
        } while ( *src++ != &#39;\0&#39; );

        return dest;
    }

In the first loop

    while( *p != &#39;\0&#39; ) ++p;

we are searching the end of the destination string because we are going to append the source string to the end of the destination string. And strings are defined as sequences of characters ended with the terminating zero character &#39;\0&#39;.

In this loop

        do
        {
            *p++ = *src;
        } while ( *src++ != &#39;\0&#39; );

We are doing the appending.

Here is a demonstrative program.

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    
    char * strcat_p( char *dest, const char *src )
    {
        char *p = dest;
    
        while( *p != &#39;\0&#39; ) ++p;
    
        do
        {
            *p++ = *src;
        } while ( *src++ != &#39;\0&#39; );
    
        return dest;
    }
    
    int main(void) 
    {
    	char str1[20] = &quot;Hello&quot;;
    
    	puts( strcat_p( str1, &quot;, world!&quot; ) );
         
    	return 0;
    }

Its output is

    Hello, world!

The purpose of the code is to make `dest` point just after the last character of the destination string so that the characters from the source string can be added from that point and forward.

The bad thing about `while(*dest++)` is that it **always** increments `dest`, i.e. even when `*dest` is NUL (`&#39;\0&#39;`), `dest` will be incremented. So, in order to &quot;get back&quot; to the NUL, a decrement of `dest` is needed after the loop.

The code:

    while(*dest++){
    }
    dest--;

is equivalent to:

    while(1){
        char tmp = *dest;        // Save current value in tmp
        dest++;                  // Increment dest
        if (tmp == &#39;\0&#39;) break;  // Check tmp and stop the loop if it&#39;s NUL
    }
    
    dest--;                       // Compensate for the unwanted increment

The code should just have been:

    while(*dest) dest++;

In that way the increment is only done when needed (so there is no longer a need for the decrement)


OT:

Make sure to initialize `str1` to something - at least do:

    char str1[20] = &quot;&quot;;

